"""
MKT Context Commentary — 1 Kings chapters 18–19
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1kings-18-19.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/1kings.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/1kings.json
- data/commentary/ellicott/1kings.json (verse-level historical details)

Key context decisions in this range:
- Ch18: Carmel contest — Baal prophets' ritual practices; Ugaritic Baal Cycle background
  already established in 17:1 script; here Mount Carmel as borderland high place;
  the Passover/limp wordplay (pasah); 12 stones as north-south unity claim;
  Deut 13 applied to false prophets at Kishon
- Ch19: Moses typology (40 days, Horeb, cave, hidden face); qol demamah daqah;
  remnant theology (7,000); adderet (mantle) as symbolic commission transfer;
  Elisha's 12-yoke wealth; Rom 11:4 reception of v18
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

KINGS = {
  "18": {
    "1": "<p>The notice of &ldquo;the third year&rdquo; has a textual history. Luke 4:25 and James 5:17 preserve a tradition of &ldquo;three years and six months&rdquo; for the drought, a precision the Kings narrative does not itself give. The six-month difference is typically resolved by reckoning Elijah&rsquo;s third-year announcement from the beginning of the Zarephath sojourn rather than from the initial declaration. The duration three-and-a-half years became a symbolic number in apocalyptic literature (Dan 7:25; Rev 11:3; 12:6) — half of seven, the period of divine testing. YHWH&rsquo;s direct speech to Elijah resumes after the Zarephath episodes; the famine&rsquo;s severity (&ldquo;severe in Samaria&rdquo;, v2) provides the political context in which Ahab is vulnerable to Elijah&rsquo;s challenge.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The drought was &ldquo;severe in Samaria&rdquo; — the capital Omri had built as a purpose-designed royal city. Unlike Shechem or Tirzah (earlier northern capitals tied to specific tribal territories), Samaria stood on land Omri purchased outright (16:24), giving the king a city with no tribal claim over it, modeled on David&rsquo;s Jerusalem. The severity of the famine there would have concentrated political pressure on Ahab — a capital city without fodder for the royal livestock was a court crisis, not merely an agricultural one.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Obadiah&rsquo;s name means &ldquo;servant of YHWH&rdquo; — significant in a court where Jezebel had been systematically eliminating YHWH&rsquo;s prophets. His role as <em>ʾăšer ʿal-habbayit</em> — the man &ldquo;over the house&rdquo; — was the highest administrative office in the Israelite and Judahite monarchies, roughly equivalent to the modern prime minister or chief steward. The same title appears for Joseph in Potiphar&rsquo;s house (Gen 39:4-5), for the steward of Joseph&rsquo;s house in Egypt (Gen 43:16), and for Jotham as regent of Judah (2 Kgs 15:5). That a man who &ldquo;greatly feared YHWH&rdquo; held this office under Ahab while Jezebel persecuted prophets illustrates the divided court — Ahab&rsquo;s complicity with Jezebel was not wholesale; he was more passive than ideological.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Jezebel&rsquo;s persecution of YHWH&rsquo;s prophets is the first recorded state campaign against the prophetic order in Israel. Previous hostility toward prophets came from individuals (Saul pursuing David; the conflicts of Solomon&rsquo;s reign), but Jezebel&rsquo;s action was systematic: she &ldquo;cut off&rdquo; (<em>hikrîtāh</em>) prophets — the same verb used of cutting off from the covenant community in legal texts. The guilds of prophets (<em>bᵉnê hannᵉḇîʾîm</em>, &ldquo;sons of the prophets&rdquo;) that appear frequently in the Elijah-Elisha narratives (2 Kgs 2:3, 4:38) represent organized prophetic communities; Obadiah&rsquo;s hiding of 100 prophets &ldquo;fifty in a cave&rdquo; suggests these were from such communities. The provision of &ldquo;bread and water&rdquo; is the minimum sustenance for survival — Obadiah&rsquo;s covert operation was an act of counter-state resistance from within the palace.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Ahab&rsquo;s priority is fodder for the royal livestock — horses and mules were the military and logistical backbone of an ancient Near Eastern monarchy. The Assyrian annals document the horse-breeding economies of northern kingdoms; Ahab himself contributed 2,000 chariots to the coalition against Shalmaneser III at Qarqar (853 BCE, the Kurkh Monolith). Losing horses and mules to famine was not merely an economic but a military catastrophe, which explains why Ahab himself joins the search. The distribution of labor — Ahab one way, Obadiah another — reflects an organized royal survey of the entire land.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The division of the land between Ahab and Obadiah for the search reflects the administrative division of Israel into twelve districts established by Solomon (1 Kgs 4:7-19). The royal survey is a bureaucratic operation, not a personal outing — each man covers his assigned territory. The narrative places Obadiah in the path of Elijah precisely because his route takes him away from Ahab, setting up the encounter that Elijah controls.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Obadiah&rsquo;s prostration (<em>wayyippōl ʿal-pānāyw</em>, &ldquo;he fell on his face&rdquo;) upon recognizing Elijah is the gesture of a subject before a superior, or a worshiper before a divine representative. The same gesture appears at YHWH-theophanies and at the appearances of divine messengers (Josh 5:14; Ezek 1:28; Dan 8:17). That Obadiah uses it toward Elijah — a fugitive prophet with a price on his head — registers Elijah&rsquo;s status in prophetic eyes as someone carrying divine authority regardless of political standing.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Elijah&rsquo;s instruction — &ldquo;tell your master: Elijah is here&rdquo; — is deliberately provocative. Ahab has been searching for Elijah across every nation and kingdom (v10); Elijah surrenders his location willingly, on his own terms. The prophetic office asserts sovereignty over the political: the prophet presents himself to the king, not the king summons the prophet. The same dynamic governs the confrontations of Samuel with Saul and Nathan with David.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Obadiah&rsquo;s fear is rational: if the Spirit of YHWH carries Elijah away before Ahab arrives, Obadiah will be executed for false report. The &ldquo;hand over your servant to Ahab&rdquo; language (<em>ûnᵉtattānî bᵉyad-ʾaḥʾāḇ lahᵃrāgēnî</em>) is the language of judicial execution — being &ldquo;handed over&rdquo; to a king meant certain death, as with Naboth (ch21) and with YHWH&rsquo;s prophets under Jezebel. Obadiah is calculating whether obeying the prophet will cost him his life.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Ahab&rsquo;s search across nations implies a degree of diplomatic or tributary authority over neighboring peoples — consistent with Omri&rsquo;s regional dominance attested by the Mesha Stele. The oath formula &ldquo;as YHWH your God lives&rdquo; is notable: Obadiah addresses Elijah with YHWH&rsquo;s name, distinguishing Elijah&rsquo;s deity from Ahab&rsquo;s court religion. The inclusion of &ldquo;your God&rdquo; signals that Obadiah is speaking from within the YHWH-worshiping community even while serving in Ahab&rsquo;s palace.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The repeated quotation of the command — &ldquo;go tell your master: Elijah is here&rdquo; — marks the sentence as the central difficulty. Obadiah is not refusing; he is explaining the risk structure. The narrative slows to convey the weight of the moment: delivering this message could cost him his life if Elijah disappears before Ahab arrives, and Obadiah has learned from experience that the Spirit can carry Elijah unexpectedly.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Obadiah&rsquo;s reference to the Spirit of YHWH carrying Elijah &ldquo;who knows where&rdquo; reflects the popular understanding of prophetic transportation. The same Spirit-carry motif appears in 2 Kgs 2:16, where the sons of the prophets search for Elijah after the whirlwind ascent, and in Acts 8:39 (Philip carried away by the Spirit after the Ethiopian eunuch&rsquo;s baptism). The phrase preserves the background belief that prophets could be moved by divine agency — a belief Elijah&rsquo;s career had apparently confirmed in popular memory.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Obadiah&rsquo;s self-defense recapitulates v4 — he repeats the detail of fifty prophets per cave, as if presenting credentials. The rhetorical structure is that of a covenant-loyalty claim: &ldquo;Has my lord not been told what I did...&rdquo; He is establishing that he is already a proven member of the resistance against Jezebel, and thus should not now be exposed to Ahab&rsquo;s wrath as a reward for his faithfulness.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The repeated protest &mdash; &ldquo;and now you say, go tell your master: Elijah is here; he will kill me&rdquo; &mdash; is an ancient rhetorical technique of stating the same fear three times to convey genuine terror. The repetition also structures Obadiah&rsquo;s speech as a formal plea, not mere complaint. Elijah&rsquo;s silence during this speech is significant: the narrative records no interruption, allowing Obadiah&rsquo;s case to be heard in full before Elijah&rsquo;s oath resolves it.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Elijah&rsquo;s oath &mdash; &ldquo;as YHWH of hosts lives, before whom I stand, I will surely show myself to Ahab today&rdquo; &mdash; uses the fuller divine title <em>YHWH ṣᵉḇāʾôt</em> (&ldquo;YHWH of armies/hosts&rdquo;), which appears rarely in the Samuel-Kings narratives but frequently in the pre-exilic prophets. The phrase &ldquo;before whom I stand&rdquo; is the standard formula of prophetic appointment and access: to stand before someone in the ancient court was to be in their permanent service and presence (cf. 1 Kgs 10:8 of Solomon&rsquo;s servants; 1 Kgs 17:1 of Elijah&rsquo;s own self-presentation). Elijah&rsquo;s oath is a counter-oath to Obadiah&rsquo;s oath of v10 — YHWH as witness on both sides of the exchange.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The narrative is brief: Obadiah delivers the message, Ahab comes to meet Elijah. The ease of Ahab&rsquo;s compliance contrasts with the elaborate search of v10 — once Elijah presents himself, Ahab abandons the posture of hunter. The power dynamic has shifted: the king now comes to the prophet&rsquo;s location, not the prophet to the palace.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Ahab&rsquo;s address — &ldquo;Is that you, you troubler of Israel&rdquo; (<em>ʿôḵēr yiśrāʾēl</em>) — uses the word <em>ʿākar</em>, to trouble or bring disaster. The same word is used of Achan in Josh 7:25 (<em>ʿăḵartānū</em>, &ldquo;you have troubled us&rdquo;) and of Jephthah&rsquo;s daughter (Judg 11:35). It is the language of someone who has brought covenant curse onto the community through violation. Ahab&rsquo;s application of it to Elijah reverses the actual dynamic: the king identifies the prophet, not Baal worship, as the source of Israel&rsquo;s disaster. This inversion — blaming the messenger of judgment for the judgment — is a recurring feature of the monarchy&rsquo;s response to prophecy.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Elijah&rsquo;s counter-identification turns Ahab&rsquo;s charge back: &ldquo;I have not troubled Israel — you and your father&rsquo;s house have, because you abandoned the commandments of YHWH and followed the Baalim.&rdquo; The phrase &ldquo;your father&rsquo;s house&rdquo; implicates the Omride dynasty collectively: the drought is covenant consequence, not prophetic curse. The Deuteronomistic framework here is explicit — abandonment of YHWH&rsquo;s commandments (Deut 11:17) triggers precisely the drought that Elijah&rsquo;s announcement in 17:1 inaugurated. Elijah is not the cause; he is the herald of a covenant mechanism already operative.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Mount Carmel — the word means &ldquo;garden-park&rdquo; or &ldquo;orchard&rdquo; (the well-planted mountain) — is a limestone ridge approximately 24 miles long running northwest to southeast, projecting into the Mediterranean at the northern end and forming the southern boundary of the Jezreel plain. It stood at the geographic junction of Phoenician coastal territory (Baal&rsquo;s heartland, immediately north) and Israelite tribal territory. As a mountain near the Phoenician border, it was an appropriate venue for a contest between YHWH and the Phoenician Baal. The four hundred and fifty prophets of Baal and four hundred prophets of Asherah represent the institutional prophetic corps maintained at royal expense — &ldquo;who eat at Jezebel&rsquo;s table&rdquo; is the court-patronage formula, identifying them as state-supported cultic officials, not independent holy men.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Ahab&rsquo;s assembly of &ldquo;all Israel&rdquo; at Carmel represents the use of royal administrative machinery — the district system and levy mechanisms — for what becomes a public theological verdict. The population witnesses the contest; their presence makes the outcome a national event, not a private quarrel between prophet and king. The gathering also places Baal&rsquo;s prophets before their supporting public, where failure cannot be hidden.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Elijah&rsquo;s challenge — &ldquo;how long will you waver between two opinions?&rdquo; (<em>ʿad-mātay ʾattem pōsᵉḥîm ʿal-šᵉtê hassᵉʿippîm</em>) — uses <em>pāsaḥ</em>, the verb from which <em>pesaḥ</em> (Passover) derives. The precise sense of <em>pāsaḥ</em> is debated: it can mean &ldquo;to limp&rdquo; (as Mephibosheth limped, 2 Sam 4:4), &ldquo;to leap over,&rdquo; or &ldquo;to dance.&rdquo; The likely picture is of limping or lurching between two positions — the image of a person whose gait is unstable because they try to plant a foot on two different paths simultaneously. The people&rsquo;s silence (they &ldquo;did not answer a word&rdquo;) is itself significant: they could not affirm either YHWH or Baal without committing publicly, so they said nothing. This collective silence in the presence of the prophet is the silence of a community whose loyalty has become purely instrumental.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Elijah&rsquo;s self-identification as &ldquo;the only prophet of YHWH left&rdquo; is technically imprecise — Obadiah has just told him about the hundred hidden prophets (v13). The statement functions rhetorically to frame the contest: one prophet of YHWH against four hundred and fifty of Baal. The odds make the expected outcome of any human-strength contest obvious, which is why the contest&rsquo;s result will be unambiguous: it cannot be attributed to superior human organization or resources on Elijah&rsquo;s side.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The contest terms are public and equal: two bulls, Baal&rsquo;s prophets choose first (an advantage), the wood is laid but no fire lit. The format follows a recognizable ancient pattern of divine adjudication through a sign: the god who &ldquo;answers by fire&rdquo; proves his reality. Fire from heaven had already inaugurated the Tabernacle&rsquo;s sacrificial system (Lev 9:24) and would later confirm Solomon&rsquo;s temple dedication (2 Chr 7:1) — the contest invokes a theologically loaded type of divine authentication that the Israelite audience would recognize.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The criterion — &ldquo;the God who answers by fire, he is God&rdquo; — is agreed upon by the assembly (&ldquo;it is well spoken&rdquo;). The public acceptance of the terms is legally significant: the verdict will be delivered in front of witnesses who consented to the method. In ancient Near Eastern judicial practice, the ordeal was a recognized means of determining truth when evidence was disputed; here the entire nation functions as the court that accepts the terms of the divine ordeal.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Elijah&rsquo;s concession — &ldquo;choose your bull first, you are the larger group&rdquo; — is ironically gracious. The larger number of Baal&rsquo;s prophets is itself a disadvantage in the contest: more personnel cannot substitute for divine power, and the larger the group the more obvious the failure. The narrative emphasizes throughout that Baal&rsquo;s prophets had every structural advantage — choice of animal, larger group, longer time — and still failed.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The Baal prophets&rsquo; ritual — calling on Baal from morning until noon and &ldquo;limping around the altar&rdquo; (<em>waypasᵉḥû ʿal-hammizḇēaḥ</em>) — uses the same <em>pāsaḥ</em> root that appears in Elijah&rsquo;s challenge of v21. The deliberate wordplay connects the people&rsquo;s wavering between YHWH and Baal with the ecstatic ritual dance of Baal&rsquo;s prophets: both &ldquo;limp&rdquo; in a kind of religious instability. The Baal Cycle (Ugaritic texts, KTU 1.1-6) describes Baal&rsquo;s conflict with Mot and his seasonal absence, which may underlie the ritual of frantic calling: the priests attempting to rouse or summon a god who may be in the underworld or asleep.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Elijah&rsquo;s midday mockery catalogs possible excuses for Baal&rsquo;s silence: &ldquo;he is a god! Perhaps he is in deep thought (<em>śîaḥ</em>), or he is busy, or traveling, or perhaps he is asleep and must be awakened.&rdquo; The final suggestion — that Baal is asleep and must be awakened — may be a pointed allusion to the Baal Cycle&rsquo;s motif of Baal being vanquished by Mot and descending into death-sleep. The term <em>śîaḥ</em> can also mean &ldquo;meditating&rdquo; (Ps 55:17; 77:12) or, in a cruder interpretation preserved in rabbinic discussion, refer to a bodily function — adding a scatological edge to the mockery. Whatever the precise nuance, the point is that Elijah treats Baal as a limited being subject to the conditions that prevent limited beings from responding: inattention, distraction, travel, sleep.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The self-laceration of Baal&rsquo;s prophets — &ldquo;they cut themselves according to their custom (<em>kᵉmišpāṭām</em>) with swords and spears until blood gushed out over them&rdquo; — represents a practice forbidden in Israelite law (Lev 19:28; Deut 14:1: &ldquo;you shall not gash yourselves&rdquo;). The term <em>mišpāṭ</em> (&ldquo;custom,&rdquo; &ldquo;ordinance,&rdquo; &ldquo;justice&rdquo;) is the same word used for YHWH&rsquo;s legal statutes — Baal worship has its own <em>mišpāṭîm</em>, its own body of practice, constituting an alternative covenantal system. The blood offering of the prophets&rsquo; own bodies represents the desperation of a religious system in which the worshipers must escalate sacrifice when the deity does not respond.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The Baal prophets &ldquo;prophesied&rdquo; (<em>wayyitnabbᵉʾû</em>) until the time of the evening offering — the <em>minhah</em> (evening grain offering) was the daily scheduled sacrifice at the Jerusalem temple (Exod 29:39-41; 2 Kgs 16:15), marking the hour of approximately 3 p.m. That Elijah&rsquo;s prayer coincides with this specific hour (v36: &ldquo;at the time of the evening offering&rdquo;) grounds his action in the legitimate calendar of Israelite worship, against which the all-day frenzy of Baal&rsquo;s prophets is measured and found empty. The verb <em>hitnabbāʾ</em> in this context suggests ecstatic or frenzied behavior rather than coherent speech — the same verb used of Saul&rsquo;s prophetic frenzy (1 Sam 18:10) and of the Israelite elders in Num 11:25-26.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The &ldquo;altar of YHWH that had been thrown down&rdquo; (<em>mizbaḥ YHWH hehārûs</em>) indicates that there had been a legitimate YHWH altar on Carmel before the Baal persecution — consistent with the pre-Deuteronomic period when multiple local YHWH altars were accepted. The Deuteronomistic reform of centralization (Deut 12) aimed to eliminate precisely these local altars, though the Kings narrative treats the Carmel altar favorably because it is specifically for YHWH and is being rebuilt against Baal. Elijah&rsquo;s repair of this altar is an act of covenant restoration: reclaiming a site previously claimed for YHWH from its ruined state under Omride neglect.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The twelve stones — one for each tribe of Jacob — are an explicit assertion of pan-Israelite covenant unity at a moment of political division. Since Jeroboam I, the northern kingdom had been politically severed from Judah for approximately seventy years; yet Elijah builds an altar of twelve stones &ldquo;according to the number of the tribes of the sons of Jacob, to whom the word of YHWH had come saying, &lsquo;Your name shall be Israel.&rsquo;&rdquo; The altar architecture is a political-theological statement: the covenant with the twelve-tribe Israel is still operative despite the divided kingdom, and YHWH&rsquo;s claim on the northern ten tribes has not been cancelled by the Jeroboam schism.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The trench capable of holding &ldquo;two measures of seed&rdquo; (<em>bêt-sātayim zāraʿ</em>) — roughly four to six gallons depending on the measure — functions as the visual marker of the quantity of water. The three saturations of the altar make the subsequent fire unambiguous: nothing naturally combustible could ignite so drenched a site, and the water filling the trench rules out hidden fire pots or other mechanical explanations. The setup is deliberately anti-illusionist — Elijah constructs maximum conditions for failure before praying for fire.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The fourfold soaking — twelve jars of water poured three times over — is structured numerology: three pourings of four jars each recalls the twelve stones, maintaining the tribal-covenant symbolism throughout the altar construction. At a time of severe drought, water poured onto the ground is a costly sacrifice in itself. The water&rsquo;s source (likely from the sea visible from Carmel or from springs in the mountain) is less important than its rhetorical function: YHWH will respond not despite the water but through it, demonstrating sovereignty over the very element the drought had withheld.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The threefold pouring repeats at Elijah&rsquo;s command, reinforcing that the saturation is deliberate and witnessed. The assistants pour the water — this is not Elijah acting alone but directing a public demonstration in which the assembly participates and can attest to what they saw. Ancient Near Eastern ritual practice often required witnesses who could certify the conditions; the crowd at Carmel serves as the authenticating witnesses to the setup.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The water running down and filling the trench is the final visual marker before Elijah&rsquo;s prayer. The scene is set for maximum contrast: sodden wood, water-filled trench, a saturated bull — against which the fire that falls must be unambiguously supernatural. The narrative slows to describe each step of the preparation precisely so that no subsequent reader can attribute the outcome to natural causes.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Elijah&rsquo;s prayer at &ldquo;the time of the evening offering&rdquo; (<em>baʿalôt hamminhah</em>) — the <em>minhah</em> sacrifice at the ninth hour (approximately 3 p.m.) — grounds the Carmel contest in the rhythms of legitimate Israelite worship. Elijah does not pray in ecstatic frenzy or call all day; he prays once, briefly, at the scheduled hour of Israel&rsquo;s daily sacrifice. The invocation &ldquo;YHWH, God of Abraham, Isaac, and Israel&rdquo; uses the threefold patriarchal formula of covenant identity (Exod 3:6, 3:15; 6:2-3), anchoring the contest not in Elijah&rsquo;s personal authority but in YHWH&rsquo;s historical covenant with the nation.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The prayer&rsquo;s goal is stated explicitly: &ldquo;that this people may know that you, YHWH, are God, and that you are turning their hearts back.&rdquo; The verb for &ldquo;turning back&rdquo; (<em>hassibōtā</em>) is the same root as <em>šûḇ</em> — the covenantal &ldquo;return&rdquo; or &ldquo;repentance&rdquo; that the prophets consistently call Israel to. Elijah&rsquo;s prayer is thus not merely for a demonstration but for a conversion: the fire is meant to be the occasion of Israel&rsquo;s covenantal return, not just a proof of divine existence. The subtle ambiguity — is YHWH turning their hearts back, or is their turning back being accomplished through this act? — is preserved in the Hebrew.</p>",
    "38": "<p>The &ldquo;fire of YHWH&rdquo; (<em>ʾēš YHWH</em>) that &ldquo;fell&rdquo; (<em>wattippōl</em>) consumed the offering, wood, stones, dust, and licked up the water in the trench. The specific enumeration — offering, wood, stones, dust, water — mirrors the preparation list of vv30-35, confirming that nothing artificially combustible remained. The parallels to the fire that consumed Moses&rsquo; tabernacle inauguration sacrifice (Lev 9:24: &ldquo;fire came out from before YHWH and consumed the burnt offering&rdquo;) and to Solomon&rsquo;s temple dedication (2 Chr 7:1) identify this fire as a re-enactment of the foundational covenant moments of Israelite worship — YHWH reclaiming his people with the same authentication he used at their founding institutions.</p>",
    "39": "<p>The people&rsquo;s response — falling facedown and crying <em>YHWH hûʾ hāʾelōhîm, YHWH hûʾ hāʾelōhîm</em> (&ldquo;YHWH, he is God; YHWH, he is God&rdquo;) — is a creedal proclamation, not merely an exclamation. The repetition of the formula gives it the force of a formal confession. In context it reverses the silence of v21 — the people who could not answer Elijah&rsquo;s challenge now speak with one voice. The formula echoes the Shema&rsquo;s declaration of YHWH&rsquo;s uniqueness (Deut 6:4) and will recur at 2 Kgs 19:15 (Hezekiah&rsquo;s prayer).</p>",
    "40": "<p>The execution of Baal&rsquo;s prophets at the Wadi Kishon applies the law of Deut 13:1-5 — the prophet or dreamer who leads Israel to other gods shall be put to death. Elijah acts as a covenant enforcer, not a vigilante: the execution follows a public determination that these prophets had &ldquo;led Israel astray.&rdquo; The Kishon wadi at the foot of Carmel had been the site of Deborah&rsquo;s victory over the Canaanite army (Judg 4-5) — a location already associated with YHWH&rsquo;s military victories over Canaanite religious and political power. The choice of location is likely deliberate.</p>",
    "41": "<p>Elijah&rsquo;s instruction to Ahab — &ldquo;go up, eat and drink, for there is the sound of a heavy rain&rdquo; — signals that the drought&rsquo;s end is already announced in Elijah&rsquo;s hearing before any physical rain appears. The prophetic reception of &ldquo;the sound&rdquo; (<em>qôl hamôn haggešem</em>) — the roar or sound of a rain downpour — before the cloud appears is consistent with the prophetic pattern of receiving the word before its manifestation (cf. 17:1: the drought is announced as decreed before it begins). Ahab&rsquo;s passive compliance — he goes to eat and drink — resumes his characteristic role as a king who responds to Elijah&rsquo;s instructions without initiating anything himself.</p>",
    "42": "<p>Elijah&rsquo;s posture of prayer — &ldquo;he crouched down on the ground and put his face between his knees&rdquo; — is an uncommon posture in biblical prayer. Most prayer is depicted standing (1 Sam 1:26) or kneeling (1 Kgs 8:54; Dan 6:10). The compacted posture, face between knees, suggests intense physical withdrawal: the prophet becomes as small as possible before the divine, or adopts the posture of intense concentration. The same posture is noted in parallel form among later Sufi dervish practice, and may reflect an ancient prophetic prayer tradition. James 5:17 applies this episode as the model for persistent intercessory prayer: &ldquo;The effective prayer of a righteous person has great power.&rdquo;</p>",
    "43": "<p>The servant&rsquo;s seven trips to look toward the sea introduce a suspense pattern that the text stretches across six unremarkable reports (&ldquo;nothing&rdquo;) before the seventh. The &ldquo;seven times&rdquo; pattern is a Hebrew completeness structure: the answer comes not at the expected human time but at the divinely determined time. From the summit of Carmel the Mediterranean is visible to the northwest; the cloud would rise on the horizon before any rain was felt inland. James 5:17-18 cites precisely this episode — the seven-round prayer discipline — as the model of persistent, faith-filled intercession.</p>",
    "44": "<p>The small cloud &ldquo;like a man&rsquo;s hand&rdquo; (<em>kᵉkap-ʾîš</em>) rising from the sea is the first physical manifestation. Elijah&rsquo;s immediate instruction to Ahab — &ldquo;prepare your chariot and go down before the rain stops you&rdquo; — acts on the prophetic knowledge that this small sign is the leading edge of YHWH&rsquo;s storm. Mediterranean weather patterns allow squalls to build rapidly from the sea across the Carmel ridge; a small cloud on the horizon could become a drenching rainstorm within an hour. Elijah reads the sign as certain before the cloud has formed.</p>",
    "45": "<p>The storm&rsquo;s rapidity — &ldquo;in a short time the sky grew dark with clouds and wind, and a great rain fell&rdquo; — confirms the Mediterranean storm pattern. Jezreel, at the eastern foot of Carmel near the Jezreel plain, was Ahab&rsquo;s second royal residence (21:1) alongside Samaria. The distance from Carmel&rsquo;s summit to Jezreel is approximately 15-17 miles — a chariot journey of an hour or more, which would be soaked if the charioteer delayed.</p>",
    "46": "<p>The &ldquo;hand of YHWH&rdquo; (<em>yad YHWH</em>) coming on Elijah to run before Ahab to Jezreel is the divine empowerment for supernatural physical performance — the same &ldquo;hand of YHWH&rdquo; language describes the overwhelming onset of prophetic experience (Ezek 1:3; 3:14; 8:1). Elijah girding his loins (<em>wayyeʾazzōr mōtnāyw</em> — tucking the robe into the belt for running) is the standard preparation for exertion (Exod 12:11; 2 Kgs 4:29). That a foot-prophet outruns a chariot to Jezreel transforms the scene into a final triumph of the prophetic over the royal: Elijah arrives first, having just restored the rain, having executed Baal&rsquo;s prophets, having turned Israel back to YHWH — and runs ahead of the king as both herald and witness to what has transpired.</p>"
  },
  "19": {
    "1": "<p>Ahab&rsquo;s report to Jezebel is the last act of a passive king: he narrates what Elijah did, including the execution of her prophets, but takes no action. Jezebel is the one who responds. The contrast between Ahab&rsquo;s reporting and Jezebel&rsquo;s threatening characterizes the Omride household throughout: Jezebel drives the agenda, Ahab enables by acquiescence. The narrative detail that Ahab &ldquo;told Jezebel all that Elijah had done&rdquo; — including the killing of the prophets — suggests he knew the consequences of this report; he is handing Elijah over to Jezebel&rsquo;s judgment by informing her.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jezebel&rsquo;s oath formula — &ldquo;so may the gods do to me and more if by tomorrow at this time I have not made your life like the life of one of them&rdquo; — is the standard ancient Near Eastern imprecatory oath: calling divine punishment on oneself if one fails to fulfill the stated action. The oath invokes her Phoenician gods, not YHWH — consistent with her religious identity. The threat is sent through a messenger rather than acting immediately; scholars have noted that this may have been intended not only as a death threat but as a warning, which Elijah heeds by fleeing rather than standing his ground as at Carmel. The juxtaposition is dramatic: the prophet who stood before 850 prophets and called down fire now flees before one woman&rsquo;s message.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Beersheba — the southernmost inhabited town of Judah, the southern boundary of the settled land (the proverbial extent of the land is &ldquo;from Dan to Beersheba&rdquo;) — was where Elijah left his servant and crossed into the wilderness alone. The journey from Jezreel to Beersheba is approximately 100 miles through Israelite and Judahite territory, a journey of several days. Leaving the servant at Beersheba signals that Elijah intends to go beyond the settled land entirely — into the Negev wilderness where no human community lives. This geographic withdrawal mirrors his psychological withdrawal from prophetic life.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The <em>rotem</em> tree (often translated &ldquo;juniper&rdquo; but more accurately the white broom, <em>Retama raetam</em>) is the most common shrub of the Sinai and Negev desert, growing to two to three meters and providing the only substantial shade in an otherwise treeless environment. Elijah&rsquo;s request to die — &ldquo;it is enough (<em>rab</em>); now, YHWH, take away my life, for I am not better than my fathers&rdquo; — is the language of exhaustion rather than despair in the clinical sense. The phrase &ldquo;I am not better than my fathers&rdquo; implies that he had hoped to be — that the Carmel victory would be the turning point, the reformation that all the earlier prophets had failed to achieve. The expectation of unique effectiveness, followed by Jezebel&rsquo;s undiminished threat, produces collapse.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The angel&rsquo;s provision under the <em>rotem</em> — bread baked on coals and a jar of water — is a minimal desert ration, not a banquet. The scene echoes Hagar&rsquo;s experience in the wilderness of Beersheba in Gen 21:14-19: a servant fleeing, lying down under a desert shrub, given water by a divine messenger at the point of death. The same wilderness, the same tree species, the same provision pattern — the text invites the comparison without making it explicit. Both narratives involve someone cast out from the center of YHWH&rsquo;s activity, sustained in the desert, and redirected back to purpose.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The description of Elijah eating briefly and lying down again captures the specific quality of deep exhaustion: even hunger cannot fully rouse him. He eats &ldquo;and lay down again&rdquo; — the minimal response of someone not yet ready to resume life. The <em>ʿûgāh</em> (cake or loaf baked on coals) is the same word used for the cakes Abraham baked for the divine visitors at Mamre (Gen 18:6) and for the bread Gideon prepared for the angel of YHWH (Judg 6:19) — a basic form of hospitality bread, here prepared not by a host but given to a guest by the divine visitor himself.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The angel&rsquo;s second appearance with the explicit reason — &ldquo;the journey is too far for you&rdquo; (<em>kî-rab mimmᵉkā hadderek</em>) — indicates that YHWH knows Elijah&rsquo;s intended destination before Elijah states it. The phrase reveals divine accommodation to human limitation: the second provision is not a reward for recovery but a provision for a journey the angel knows Elijah intends to make. This anticipatory knowledge drives the narrative: Elijah has not told anyone he is going to Horeb, yet the provision is specifically calibrated for that journey.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The forty days and forty nights to Horeb (Sinai) is explicit Moses typology. Moses was on Sinai forty days and forty nights (Exod 24:18; 34:28; Deut 9:9, 9:18); the same duration is associated with the original covenant-giving. By traveling forty days to reach the sacred mountain, Elijah re-enacts the Mosaic journey and arrives at the mountain of YHWH&rsquo;s covenant revelation. Horeb is the Deuteronomic name for the mountain that Exodus calls Sinai — both names refer to the same location, the mountain of the covenant in the Sinai peninsula. &ldquo;In the strength of that food&rdquo; (<em>bᵉkōaḥ hāʾăkîlāh hahîʾ</em>) emphasizes that the supernatural provision sustained a journey no ordinary food could support.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The &ldquo;cave&rdquo; (<em>hamᵉʿārāh</em>) at Horeb has the definite article, suggesting a specific and known cave. This is almost certainly a reference to the cleft of the rock in which Moses was hidden when YHWH&rsquo;s glory passed by in Exod 33:22 (&ldquo;I will put you in the cleft of the rock, and cover you with my hand until I have passed by&rdquo;). Elijah arrives at the exact location where Moses experienced YHWH&rsquo;s self-revelation under the divine name. The question &ldquo;what are you doing here, Elijah?&rdquo; is not a request for information but a gentle challenge — the same question YHWH asks Adam in Gen 3:9 (&ldquo;where are you?&rdquo;) and Hagar in Gen 16:8 (&ldquo;where have you come from and where are you going?&rdquo;): a divine invitation to self-disclosure and reconsideration.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Elijah&rsquo;s complaint lists the covenant violations: Israel abandoned YHWH&rsquo;s covenant, threw down his altars, killed his prophets with the sword, and &ldquo;I alone am left, and they are seeking my life.&rdquo; The word <em>qinnēʾtî</em> (&ldquo;I have been very zealous,&rdquo; or &ldquo;I have been exceedingly jealous&rdquo;) uses <em>qānāʾ</em>, the root of &ldquo;jealousy&rdquo; — the term used of YHWH&rsquo;s own jealous exclusivity (&ldquo;I am a jealous God,&rdquo; Exod 20:5). Elijah claims the same passionate exclusivity toward YHWH that YHWH claims toward Israel: he has matched his zeal to YHWH&rsquo;s own attribute. The repeated claim &ldquo;I alone am left&rdquo; is corrected by YHWH in v18 — Elijah&rsquo;s self-assessment is wrong, but the narrative does not rebuke him for it; the correction comes as gracious revelation rather than reproof.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The great wind, earthquake, and fire of the Horeb theophany are classical elements of YHWH&rsquo;s warrior-storm manifestation: wind, earthquake, and fire appear together in Ps 18:7-15 and in the Sinai theophany of Exod 19:16-19. These are the expected modes of divine appearance — the theophanic toolkit that Israel&rsquo;s tradition had encoded. Yet the narrative insists: YHWH was not in the wind, not in the earthquake, not in the fire. This is not a denial of earlier storm theophanies but a statement that at this moment, with this prophet, the divine word comes differently. The Baal Cycle&rsquo;s Baal rules precisely the storm, earthquake-shaking mountain, and lightning-fire — by not appearing in these forms, YHWH implicitly distinguishes himself from Baal even on the mountain of covenant.</p>",
    "12": "<p>After the fire comes <em>qôl dᵉmāmāh daqqāh</em> — typically translated &ldquo;a still small voice&rdquo; (KJV) or &ldquo;a gentle whisper.&rdquo; The three-word phrase is more precisely: <em>qôl</em> (sound/voice), <em>dᵉmāmāh</em> (stillness/silence, from <em>dāmam</em>, to be still or silent), <em>daqqāh</em> (thin/fine/slender, from <em>dāqaq</em>, to crush fine). A closer rendering would be &ldquo;the sound of a thin silence&rdquo; or &ldquo;a voice of fine stillness.&rdquo; It is an almost oxymoronic phrase — a sound that is silence, a voice that is stillness. The effect is of YHWH&rsquo;s word arriving in the mode least expected after the dramatic natural phenomena: not in overwhelming force but in quiet, requiring attention rather than commanding it by spectacle. This moment became the foundation for mystic traditions in both Jewish and Christian spirituality — the <em>via negativa</em> emphasis that the divine is encountered not in religious noise but in quiet receptivity.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Elijah&rsquo;s wrapping of his face in his <em>ʾadderet</em> (mantle/cloak) upon hearing the voice echoes Moses&rsquo; hiding of his face at the burning bush when &ldquo;he was afraid to look at God&rdquo; (Exod 3:6). The cave at Horeb, the hidden face, the divine question — the narrative has set Elijah in the exact position of Moses at the original theophany, with the same encounter structure: a prophet at the sacred mountain, face hidden, receiving a new commission. That Elijah goes to the entrance of the cave mirrors Exod 33:9-10 (Moses in the tent of meeting, the pillar of cloud standing at the entrance). The typology is dense and deliberate.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Elijah repeats his complaint from v10 verbatim. The repetition signals that the dramatic theophany — wind, earthquake, fire, still small voice — has not changed his assessment of the situation. He reports what he sees: Israel has abandoned the covenant, the altars are destroyed, the prophets are dead, he is alone, his life is threatened. This stubborn facticity is not faithlessness but honest prophetic observation. YHWH does not correct his facts; the correction is structural — Elijah does not know about the seven thousand (v18), and he needs a new commission rather than a new theology.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The commission to return by the way of the Damascus wilderness assigns Elijah three tasks: anoint Hazael as king over Aram, anoint Jehu as king over Israel, anoint Elisha as prophet. The command &ldquo;go, return on your way&rdquo; (<em>lēḵ šûḇ lᵉdarkᵉkā</em>) is the exact reversal of Elijah&rsquo;s flight — &ldquo;go back,&rdquo; the same <em>šûḇ</em> root that the prophets use for covenant return. The political scope of the commission is extraordinary: Elijah is to intervene in the regime change of a foreign nation (Aram-Damascus) and of his own (Israel) — prophetic authority extending over the international sphere, consistent with Amos 1-2 and Jeremiah&rsquo;s appointment as prophet &ldquo;to the nations.&rdquo;</p>",
    "16": "<p>Of the three commissions, Elijah personally fulfills only the call of Elisha. Hazael is anointed by Elisha (2 Kgs 8:8-13) and Jehu by a messenger of Elisha (2 Kgs 9:1-6) — Elijah&rsquo;s prophetic ministry is carried forward through his successor, not completed in his own lifetime. This is the prophetic succession pattern: the prophet does not need to complete all YHWH&rsquo;s purposes himself; he transmits the commission. Jehu son of Nimshi appears in the Assyrian Black Obelisk of Shalmaneser III (ca. 841 BCE), which shows &ldquo;Yaʾua son of Ḫumrî&rdquo; (Jehu of the house of Omri) paying tribute — one of the earliest confirmed images of an Israelite king in extrabiblical archaeology.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The triple instrument of divine judgment — Hazael&rsquo;s sword, Jehu&rsquo;s sword, Elisha&rsquo;s ministry — represents the coordinated action of foreign political power, internal military revolution, and the prophetic word. The sequence is specific: those who escape Hazael&rsquo;s Aramean raids will fall to Jehu&rsquo;s Israelite revolt; those who escape both will be reached by Elisha. The vision is of thoroughgoing covenant judgment on the Baal-worshiping nation, carried out through three different agents across a generation. The three instruments echo the Deuteronomic pattern of covenant curses: sword, plague, and famine as modes of divine judgment (Deut 28:21-26; Ezek 14:21).</p>",
    "18": "<p>The revelation of &ldquo;seven thousand in Israel — every knee that has not bowed to Baal and every mouth that has not kissed him&rdquo; — corrects Elijah&rsquo;s &ldquo;I alone am left.&rdquo; The number seven thousand is a round number signifying completeness, not a census figure: the point is that YHWH has maintained a substantial hidden remnant throughout the Baal apostasy. The criterion — knees and mouths — refers to the postures of Baal worship: kneeling before the idol and kissing it (cf. Hos 13:2: &ldquo;those who sacrifice to men kiss calves&rdquo;). Paul cites this passage in Rom 11:4 as the precedent for the remnant of grace in his own day: &ldquo;I have kept for myself seven thousand men who have not bowed the knee to Baal&rdquo; — applying it directly to the faithful Jewish remnant who accepted the Messiah. It becomes the foundational text for remnant theology as election by grace rather than by majority status.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Elisha son of Shaphat was plowing with twelve yoke of oxen — and was himself with the twelfth yoke, directing the last team. Twelve yoke of oxen indicate a large estate: this is a wealthy farming family, not subsistence agriculture. The casting of Elijah&rsquo;s <em>ʾadderet</em> (mantle, cloak — the same garment Elijah uses to hide his face in v13) over Elisha is the symbolic act of commissioning and adoption. In ANE contexts, a superior&rsquo;s garment cast over a person could signify protection, adoption, or the transfer of authority (cf. Ruth 3:9, where Ruth asks Boaz to spread his garment-wing over her — a marriage/adoption request; Ezek 16:8, where YHWH spreading his garment over Israel signifies covenantal union). No words are spoken: the mantle communicates the commission entirely.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Elisha&rsquo;s request — &ldquo;let me kiss my father and mother, and then I will follow you&rdquo; — and Elijah&rsquo;s half-ironic reply &mdash; &ldquo;go back; what have I done to you?&rdquo; — is the paradigmatic call-and-response that Jesus explicitly references in Luke 9:61-62 (&ldquo;another said, &lsquo;I will follow you, Lord, but first let me say farewell to those at my home&rsquo;&mdash; Jesus said, &lsquo;no one who puts his hand to the plow and looks back is fit for the kingdom of God&rsquo;&rdquo;). The plow imagery of Luke 9:62 directly recalls Elisha at the twelfth yoke. Elijah&rsquo;s reply — &lsquo;go back; what have I done to you?&rsquo; — is not permission to return but a test: the mantle has been cast; Elijah will not hold Elisha by force. Elisha&rsquo;s subsequent action (v21) shows he understood this correctly.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Elisha&rsquo;s response is decisive: he slaughters the oxen, burns the wooden plow and yoke as fuel for the fire, and holds a farewell feast for his people. The burning of the agricultural equipment is the physical destruction of any possibility of return to the former life — a deliberate, irreversible act. The same pattern appears when Matthew leaves his tax booth (Matt 9:9) and when the disciples leave their nets (Mark 1:18); Elisha&rsquo;s departure is the OT precedent for the total break that prophetic and apostolic calling requires. He &ldquo;arose and went after Elijah and served him&rdquo; (<em>wayyᵉšārᵉtēhû</em>) — using the same service-word applied to Joshua&rsquo;s service of Moses (Exod 24:13; Num 11:28) and Samuel&rsquo;s service of Eli (1 Sam 2:11). The disciple-succession pattern is established with the call of Elisha.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', '1kings')
    merge_comm(existing, KINGS)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '1kings', existing)
    v_count = sum(len(vv) for vv in KINGS.values())
    print(f'1 Kings 18-19 mkt-context written ({v_count} verses).')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
